Hedonic Model for Home Price Prediction - Philadelphia

Jonathan Manurung

December 2023

Introduction: Home Price Prediction Tools for Philadelphia

Philadelphia has a whole lot to offer, from public amenities such as parks and green spaces, accessibility to public transportation facilities, dinings and entertainment spots, to cultural and sport places and events. Philadelphia is also one of the most walkable cities in the nation, and still offer affordability and diversity in the city. These facts attract more people to live and work in this city.

Finding an ideal housing is the main challenge when people decided to move to this city. A house with a lot of surrounding public amenities, safe neighborhood, and offer a lot of internal features will be desirable, but in what price? Navigating house prices in this city can be challenging, thus a price prediction tool will be helpful to give initial information to the buyer.

This projects objective is to create a tool to estimate a homes market value based on a valuation model. Many similar housing market prediction tools are not as accurate as they could be because local intelligence factors are not associated well enough. An accurate model should incorporate public, Multiple Listing Service, and user-submitted data into a mathematical model, and also take home factors such as internal characteristic, location, and trends into account. Local tradition, lifestyle pattern, and proximity to favorite public amenities are important factors that must be taken into account in building the model. Deciding which internal factors, the preferences of citys residents for various public amenities and neighborhoods presents a challenges in generating an appropriate model. This project associates significant variables from houses internal characteristics, houses proximity to public amenities and disamenities, and the recent transactions information.

Data: Internal Characteritics, Proximity to Amenities, and Recent Transaction

This project involved a range of data sources for finding key insights of the home price prediction model building. Primarily in the houses internal characteristic such as sale price, number of bedrooms, floors, house type, zoning, lot size, interior and exterior condition, and houses age. These information gathered from the Philadelphia property assessment data.

This predictive tool will also incorporate proximity to public amenities variables such as parks, public transit facilities, universities, and health facilities. Proximity to city parks gives easier access to nature and recreation which have number of amenities and facilities. Living close to health facilities gives a convenience and immediate access to healthcare. These factor will also increase the opportunity to generate passive income from providing housing for health workers, patients and families, and also to attract investors. This economic opportunity also applies to buildings near universities or colleges, as they have the potential to generate passive income by providing student housing. Meanwhile, living in buildings which are just steps away from train stations and bus stops will be beneficial for frequent commuters. As the result, people are willing to pay premium price for houses near this public transit amenities. While proximity to public amenities offers clear benefits, a high crime rate is one of the most significant drawbacksor disamenities of a property.Therefore, the number of crime incidents in the neighborhood and how close a house sits from a crime locations, particularly drugs violation, serves as a variable in this framework. These information mainly gathered from Philadelphia open data portal and then underwent data wrangling to produce more useful insights.

Two feature engineering techniques were applied to define the relationship and exposure of public amenities and (dis)amenities variables to the house prices. First technique would sum the value of the amenities within a fixed buffer distance (0.125 mile) of each home sale observation. Variables like number of parks and number of universities can use this approach because their influence is generally localized and can be meaningfully captured within a defined area. Meanwhile amenity variables such as train (subway), health facilities, and (dis)amenities such as crime incidents can be more meaningfully explained by their distance to each home sale observation using k-nearest neighbor distance. Aggregating crime incidents within a fixed buffer distance from each home sale observation will create uniformity of home prices citywide, which is not likely accurate too.

Variables: Numerical and Categorical

Understanding variables that influence house prices requires a clear overview of the data used in the analysis. The table below summarizes all relevant variables used in building this predictive model, including their descriptions and key statistics (See Table 1). Variables are categorized as numerical, for features such as age of house, total livable area, distance from crime incidents, number of park within buffer, distance from nearest train station, number of university building within buffer, and distance from nearest health facility. Meanwhile, the categorical variable including number of stories, number of bedrooms, interior condition, exterior condition, building style (type), and zoning area. For clarity, the variables are grouped by internal characteristics and proximity to amenities/public services and (dis)amenities aspects that may impact property values.

numeric_variable <- c("Age", "total_livable_area","crime_nn1", "park.Buffer", "subway_nn1", "univ.Buffer", "health_nn1")

categorical_variable <- c("number_stories", "number_of_bedrooms", "interior_condition", "exterior_condition", 
                      "building_code_description_new", "zoning")


internal_characteristics <- c("Age", "total_livable_area", "number_stories", "number_of_bedrooms",
                              "interior_condition", "exterior_condition", "building_code_description_new",
                              "zoning")
proximity_amenities <- c("crime_nn1","park.Buffer", "subway_nn1", "univ.Buffer", "health_nn1")

variable_table <- c(numeric_variable, categorical_variable)

data_subset <- home_price[, variable_table]
data_subset$geometry <- NULL  # remove sf geometry if needed


variable_descriptions <- data.frame(
  Variable = variable_table,
  Description = c("Age of house", "Total livable area", "Nearest crime count (KNN)", 
                  "Number of parks within buffer", "Distance to nearest subway", 
                  "Number of universities within buffer", "Distance to nearest health facility",
                  "Number of stories", "Number of bedrooms", "Interior condition", 
                  "Exterior condition", "Building type description", "Zoning code"),
  Category = ifelse(variable_table %in% proximity_amenities, 
                    "Proximity to Amenities", 
                    "Internal Characteristics"),
  stringsAsFactors = FALSE
)


numeric_summary <- data.frame(
  Variable = numeric_variable,
  Mean = sapply(data_subset[, numeric_variable], mean, na.rm = TRUE),
  Median = sapply(data_subset[, numeric_variable], median, na.rm = TRUE),
  SD = sapply(data_subset[, numeric_variable], sd, na.rm = TRUE),
  Min = sapply(data_subset[, numeric_variable], min, na.rm = TRUE),
  Max = sapply(data_subset[, numeric_variable], max, na.rm = TRUE)
)


categorical_summary <- data.frame(
  Variable = categorical_variable,
  Most_Frequent = sapply(data_subset[, categorical_variable], function(x) {
    ux <- na.omit(x)
    ux_tab <- table(ux)
    names(ux_tab)[which.max(ux_tab)]
  }),
  Count = sapply(data_subset[, categorical_variable], function(x) {
    ux <- na.omit(x)
    ux_tab <- table(ux)
    max(ux_tab)
  })
)


summary_stats <- variable_descriptions %>%
  left_join(numeric_summary, by = "Variable") %>%
  left_join(categorical_summary, by = "Variable")


summary_stats$Category <- factor(summary_stats$Category, levels = c("Internal Characteristics", "Proximity to Amenities"))
summary_stats <- summary_stats %>% arrange(Category)


kable(summary_stats, format = "html", caption = "Table 1. Summary Statistics of Variables by Category") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, position = "left")

Correlation across variables

Correlation among the variables are important in building accurate house price predictive mode, as it helps identify features that may be useful for predicting the sale prices. A matrix is created to visualize correlation across numeric variables used in building this predictive model (See Figure 1). Correlation between different public amenities and (dis)amenities to the house sale price can be understood by the visualization in this scatterplots (see Figure 2). By visualizing these relationships, we can identify patterns and detect how meaningful our predictors are in determining housing prices across Philadelphia.

Correlation matrix in Figure 1 shows a diverse set of relationship among numerical variables. Strongest positive correlation can be seen between distance to train station and distance to health facilities. This indicates that proximity to train stations has a consistent relationship with crime incidents whether closer or farther.

The scatterplots in Figure 2 show the positive correlation between house price and distance from features like crime incidents and health facilities, and negative correlation with the distance to subway station. The sale price increases when the distance from crime incidents and health facilities tend to increase. Otherwise, as the distance from train station increase, sale price tends to increase. The scatterplot also shows the positive relationship between house sale price and park and university, as it increases if the number of park and university in buffer area increase.

Visualizing House Sale Price Variables

The maps and charts provide a clear visualization of the primary data, highlighting the house prices across the city, the average house price in every Philadelphias neighborhood, and the house prices distribution across the city. Houses with higher price located in Rittenhouse and around Center City, also in the Northwest of Center City, particularly in Chesnut Hill, Mount Airy West, Manayunk and some part of the Germantown neighborhood. Meanwhile, majority of the house prices are clustered below $500,000 (see Figure 3)

These following maps show clear visualization of the independent variables from both internal characteristics such as total livable area and interior condition, and public amenities or (dis)amenities such as drug violation crime incidents across the city of Philadelphia (see Figure 4)

These maps provide visualization of how each independent variables discussed distributed across Philadelphia. Houses with larger total livable area located around Mount Airy West, Chesnut Hill, Germantown, and Manayunk. Significant numbers also located in Rittenhouse and Spruce Hill. House with good exterior condition (1 = best, 7 = worst) are located around Lower North Philadelphia, primarily in Spring Garden and Ludlow. Significant number of houses also located in Manayunk, Ritten House, and South Philadelphia around Point Breeze neighborhood. The map also shows the (dis)amenity factor of drug violation incidents, which are concentrated in Upper Kensington.

Methods: Building the Model

Having explored and summarized the independent variables, a prediction tool for house prices is developed based on a hedonic model. A hedonic model estimates house prices as a function of both property characteristics and neighborhood features (Rosen, 1974). In building this house predictive tool, Linear Regression or Ordinary Least Squares Regression (OLS) approach, is used to model the relationship between house prices and the selected independent variables.

The first step of building the model is to clean the dataset. This step is critical to ensure all the downstream work will give accurate result. This step includes treating NAs or missing values in a Missing category, to avoid misleading values and allow the model to learn patterns associated with missingness. Further feature engineering is performed to the cleaned data to simplify the number of categories in all categorical independent variables, thus reducing model complexity, improve generalization and avoid overfitting, and provide easier interpretation.

Both Interior and Exterior Condition variable is simplified into four categories: Above Average, Average, Below Average, and Missing. Number of Stories variable is simplified into four categories: 4+ Floors, 3 Floors, Up to 2 Floors, and Missing. There are four categories remaining for Number of Bedrooms variable: Large, Medium, Small, and Missing. Both House Type/Style and Zoning variables are treated differently as they have more unique categories: categories with frequency less than 10%, classified into Other category to handle rare occurrences. This process leave both variables with less categories. Bar chart is created to visualize the sale price as a function of new categorical variables (see Figure 5)

Results: Model Building Interpretation

Cleaned dataset then splitted into two datsets: Modelling dataset and Prediction dataset. The Modelling dataset, which contains the complete sale price information, is split into Training and Testing datasets with a 60:40 ratio to build the house price model. OLS model is trained using the selected independent variables, and the statistical summary explained in the table (See Table 2)

Generalizability: Cross-validation

K-Fold Cross-validation is conducted to ensure this modeling approach perform well on new and unseen data. Data from the home price dataset splitted into k=100 equal sized subsets. For a given fold, model trained on a subset of observations, and predict on a test set, and measure goodness of fit. The average goodness of fit across all k fold then calculated as explained in the table and graph below (see Table 5 and Figure 6).

Table 5. Linear Regression Cross-Validation Summary
Metric Value
RMSE 0.411
Rsquared 0.721
MAE 0.297

Model that is generalizable to a new data will show comparable goodness of fit metrics across each fold. Based on cross validation with a k of 100 fold, we find a mean absolute percent error around

The linear regression model was evaluated using 100-fold cross-validation on 16,447 samples with 14 predictors. The cross-validation results show an RMSE of 0.409, an R-squared of 0.723, and a mean absolute error (MAE) of 0.296. This indicates that the model explains approximately 72% of the variation in sale prices, with typical prediction errors of around 0.296 in log-sale price units. The RMSE, which penalizes larger errors more heavily, suggests that on average, predictions are moderately close to the observed values. Overall, the results demonstrate that the model captures most of the signal in the data and is likely to generalize well to unseen observations, though some residual variation remains that may reflect factors not included in the model.

Predicted prices are plotted as a function of observed prices (See Figure 7). The orange line represents the observed prices while the green line represents the predicted fit.

Spatial Lag: Do prices & errors cluster?

A map of residual error from test set (see Figure 8) shows that the errors from this model are randomly distributed in space. It indicates that the model has captured the spatial structure and has accounted the local factor to the neighborhood scale. This spatial autocorrelation test should consider a home price with nearby home prices. Utilizing nearest neighbors concept, spatial lag of house prices can be measured and plotted (see Figure 9). The result indicates that as home price errors increase, so does nearby home price errors.

ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = neighborhood, fill = "darkgray")+
  geom_sf(data = home_price_test, aes(color = q5(sale_price.Error)),
          show.legend = "point", size = .75) +
  scale_color_manual(values = palette5,
                     labels = qBr(home_price_test, "sale_price.Error"),
                     name= "Sale Price")+
  labs(title = "Map of Residual Test Set", subtitle = "Dollars, Philadelphia", caption = "Figure 8")+
  mapTheme()+
  theme(plot.caption = element_text(size = 8, hjust = 0))

Another approach to measure spatial autocorrelation is using Morans I. Its based on a null hypothesis that a given spatial process is randomly distributed. From the result of Morans I test of the model, which is close to 0, indicates that the resulted errors are randomly distributed (see Figure 10).

Generalizability of the model

Measuring the generalizability, in this context the ability to predict with comparable accuracy across different neighborhood context, is important to see if a geospatial predictive model generalize to different neighborhood context. In general, generalizability across space is very challenging with OLS, because it focuses on relationship at the mean. These map and scatter plot presents the mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) by neighborhood and as a function of mean price by neighborhood from the test set predictions (see Figure 12 and Figure 13).

The second approach to test the generalizability is by using census data to test how well the model generalizes to different group contexts, in this case, race and income. Using tidycensus, the study area are splitted into two groups, race context and income context (see Figure 14). These plots shows that Philadelphia is segregated with respect to both race and income.

Discussion: Is this an effective model?

As mentioned before, generalizability across space is very challenging with OLS because it focuses on relationship at the mean. What makes the home prices so difficult to predict is that prices are clustered at different spatial scales. This model has accounted for the neighborhood scale, but other spatial relationships, that exist at smaller scales, have not been accounted.

This model is not fully generalizable as we can see a relatively huge different in MAPE across groups (race and income). This might happened because the model may rely heavily on features correlated with White-majority neighborhood and high-income neighborhoods. Spatial or socioeconomic factors not captured in the model might affect prices differently in Non-White majority neighborhood and low-income neighborhood.

As conclusion, this model is not recommended to Zillow because it predicts relatively poorly. There are some recommendation to improve this model, including: consider adding more features that capture neighborhood characteristic, and involve more samples across groups in the neighborhood for data training set.
